I studied general information about dataframe. The quality of data is good. Dataframe has 16715 rows. There are 12,1% missing values. There are no duplicate values. The column Name has two missing values (<0,1%). The column Year of release has 269 missing values (1,6%). The column Genre has 2 missing values (<0,1%). The column Critic_score has 8578 missing values (51.3%). The column User_Score has 6701 missing values (40.1%) and has and has both numeric and string values ('tbd' - 2424 values). The column Rating has 6766 missing values (40.5%).

# Study of year_of_release column. It has 269 missing value
# Restore missing values by function.

def year_from_name(row):
    
    '''
    The function restore missing values in year_of_release column.
            
    '''
    game = row[0]
    plat = row[1]
    year = row[2]
    
    
    if pd.isna(year) == True:
        
        # step 1. attempt to restore value by value of the same game on other platforms
        df_game = df[df['name'].str.contains(game)] 
        year_game = df_game['year_of_release'].mean() 
        if pd.notna(year_game) == True:
            return year_game
            
        # step 2. attempt to restore value by extract year from name of game        
        for y in range(1980, 2017): # pattern 19xx, 20xx 
            y = str(y)
            if y in game:
                return y
                    
        for x in range(80, 99+1): # pattern 99, ...  
            x = str(x)
            if x in game:
                return '19'+x
                         
        for z in range(0, 10): # pattern 05, 07, ...
            z = '0'+str(z)
            if z in game:
                return '20'+z
                        
        for q in range(11, 17): # pattern 10, 11, ...
            q = str(q)
            if q in game:
                return '20'+q
            
        for s in range(1, 10): # pattern 2k6, ...
            s=str(s)
            s1 = '2k'+s
            if s1 in game:
                return '200'+s
               
        # step 3. attempt to restore value by value of the game
        # with the same first word in the name 
        game_cut = game.split(' ', 1)[0]
        df_game = df[df['name'].str.contains(game_cut)]
        year_game = df_game['year_of_release'].mean()
        if pd.notna(year_game) == True:
            return year_game
            
        # step 4. remaining names restore by mean year of platform 
        df_game = df[df['platform'] == plat]
        year_game = df_game['year_of_release'].mean() 
        if pd.notna(year_game) == True:
            return year_game
        
    else:
        return year

df['year_of_release'] = df.apply(year_from_name, axis=1).astype('int')

# I decided to fill missing values by 0 for score columns because it's more suitable for processing. 
# But for analysis, I will use values without null-values.

df['user_score'] = df['user_score'].fillna(0)

In [10]:
# Restore missing values for Rating column

df['rating'] = df['rating'].fillna('no rating')
df['rating'] = df['rating'].replace('k-a', 'e') # because K-A rating was changed to E rating in 1998.
df['rating'] = df['rating'].replace('rp', 'no rating') # because RP rating it's really no rating

                                  aggfunc='min').reset_index() # get info about first releses

    name_first_release.groupby(['year_of_release'])['name'].count()) # join ones

Through the use boxplot I have got an interested picture of the life cycles of platforms. For example game console Atari 2600 formally had a life cycle from 1980 to 2011. Thus, the platform lived for 31 years. But the boxplot said to us another. Really time life of the platform was about 7 years: from 1980 to 1987. # How are the platforms distributed in the market?
df_market = df[df['total_sales'] != 0]
total_sales = df_market.pivot_table(index='platform', values='total_sales',
                          aggfunc='sum').sort_values('total_sales').reset_index()
total_sales['platform'] = total_sales.apply(lambda x: str(x[0]) if int(x[1])>20 else 'other', axis=1)
total_sales = total_sales.pivot_table(index='platform', values='total_sales',
                          aggfunc='sum').sort_values('total_sales').reset_index()
sizes = total_sales['total_sales'].values.tolist()
labels = total_sales.apply(lambda x: str(x[0])+'\n'+'$'+str(round(x[1])), axis=1)

plt.title('Distribution shares of platforms in the market, $M', fontdict={'size':15})
plt.show()

There are monster companies on the market with several generations of consoles that occupy the lion's share of the market: Sony (Play Station), Microsoft (X Box), Nintando (Wii, DS). Other smaller players have a small market.

df_group = df.groupby(['platform', 'year_of_release'])['total_sales'].sum().reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(13, 10))
sns.boxplot(x='platform', y='total_sales', data=df_group, order=ordered1['platform'], palette='colorblind')
plt.title('Global sales by platforms', fontdict={'size':20})
plt.ylabel('Total sales, $M')          
plt.xlabel('Platforms')
plt.show()

How we can see in the picture we can split of result for 3 parts. Platforms with huge sales (from left to the right: from PS2 to PS), platforms with medium sales (from GBA to XOne), and platforms with small sales (from 2600 to PC FX).
Huge sales platforms confirm the result of Z-score analysis about the leading sales.
The average values of all the platforms shift to the different sides of the center.
There is no common rule. This shift can have different reasons such as the general rise or fall of the market, next-generation platform launch.

Several platforms had the powered start of sales. PS4, 3DS, Xbox One, WiiU started from good levels straight away. Several platforms had outliers sales for some years.

  • The top five platforms. Describe variations in their market shares from region to region.
  • The top five genres. Explain the difference.
  • Do ESRB ratings affect sales in individual regions?

def autolabel(rects):
    """Attach a text label above each bar in *rects*, displaying its height."""
    for rect in rects:
        height = rect.get_height()
        ax.annotate('{:.0f}'.format(height),
                    xy=(rect.get_x() + rect.get_width() / 2, height),
                    xytext=(0, 3),  # 3 points vertical offset
                    textcoords="offset points",
                    ha='center', va='bottom')


autolabel(rects1)
autolabel(rects2)
autolabel(rects3)

fig.tight_layout()

plt.show()

#  Study how ESRB rating affects sales.  

# Make dataset for analysis of the distribution of ESRB rating by regions.
df_rate = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Name', 'Years', 'Rating', 'Region', 'Sales'])
for row in df.itertuples():
    
    if row.year_of_release < 2000:
        year = 'Before 2000'
    elif row.year_of_release <= 2010:
        year = '2000 - 2010'
    elif row.year_of_release > 2010:
        year = 'After 2010'
        
    if row.na_sales > 0:
        df_rate = df_rate.append({'Name': row.name,
                                  'Years': year,
                                  'Rating': row.rating,
                                  'Region': 'North America',
                                  'Sales': row.na_sales},
                                 ignore_index=True)
            
    if row.eu_sales > 0:
        df_rate = df_rate.append({'Name': row.name,
                                  'Years': year,
                                  'Rating': row.rating,
                                  'Region': 'Europe',
                                  'Sales': row.eu_sales},
                                 ignore_index=True)
        
    if row.jp_sales > 0:
        df_rate = df_rate.append({'Name': row.name,
                                  'Years': year,
                                  'Rating': row.rating,
                                  'Region': 'Japan',
                                  'Sales': row.jp_sales},
                                 ignore_index=True)
        
        
df_rate=df_rate.query('Sales < 20') # Drop some outliers

ax.set_ylabel('Average sales, $M')
ax.set_title('Comparison of Average Sales for Different ESRB Ratings by Region', fontdict={'size':15})
ax.set_xticks(x)
ax.set_xticklabels(labels)
ax.legend()

fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()

How we can see 'Mature' rating games were a more profitable product for North America and Europe. For Japanese market lead 'Everyone' rating games.

5. Testing the hypotheses¶

  1. Let's check hypothesis.

Null hypothesis: Average user ratings of the Xbox One and PC platforms are the same.¶

Alternative hypothesis: Average user ratings of the Xbox One and PC platforms are the different.

Alpha = 0,05.
Because this is the most common alpha value for analysis.

In [39]:
df_user = df[df['user_score'] != 0]
sample_xbox = df_user.query('platform == "x360" or platform == "xone"')['user_score']
sample_pc = df_user.query('platform == "pc"')['user_score']

alpha = .05
results = st.ttest_ind(
        sample_xbox, 
        sample_pc,
        )

print('p-value: ', results.pvalue)
if (results.pvalue < alpha):
        print('We reject the null hypothesis')
else:
        print("We can't reject the null hypothesis")

p-value:  4.30113816248073e-09
We reject the null hypothesis

Our hypothesis didn't confirm. The probability of crossing of values of distribution very small.
I think there are different users for Xbox and PC. Users for PC more adults than for game consoles, because PC is not only a game platform but also a tool for work. A lot of adults are gaming on PC.

  1. Let's check another hypothesis.

Null hypothesis: Average user ratings for the Action and Sports genres are the same.¶

Alternative hypothesis: Average user ratings for the Action and Sports genres are the different.

Also Alpha = 0,05.

In [40]:
df_user = df[df['user_score'] != 0]

sample_action = df_user[(df_user['genre'] == 'action')]['user_score']
sample_sports = df_user[df_user['genre'] == 'sports']['user_score']

alpha = .05

results = st.ttest_ind(
        sample_action, 
        sample_sports,
        )

print('p-value: ', results.pvalue)

if (results.pvalue < alpha):
        print('We reject the null hypothesis')
else:
        print("We can't reject the null hypothesis")

p-value:  0.10406951359049141
We can't reject the null hypothesis

The hypothesis about the coincidence of average user ratings for the Action and Sports genres are confirmed. The p-value tells us that although the average scores for the two genres are different, there is more than a 10% probability of randomly getting a crossing of average values of user's scores.

6. General conclusion and recommendations.¶

I have exacted research on the market of games for the period 1980 - 2016. The initial goal of the study is to find growth points and business development prospects for an online game store that sells games for different platforms around the world.

Most of the research results (for the period up to 2010) are unlikely to be useful for developing direct recommendations and making forecasts, but they give an idea of such concepts as the life cycle of platforms, the popularity of genres, and the impact of reviews on sales.

Since the beginning of the study period in 1980, the games industry has grown steadily until the pivotal year for the industry in 2008. 2008 - 2009 were the most successful years for the market. During these years, the maximum number of unique games was released, as well as the maximum number of their porting to platforms. After those years in general the market was only shrinking.

In [41]:
sns.relplot(data=num_release_by_years, kind='line')
plt.title('How many games were released in different years?', fontdict={'size':15})
plt.ylabel('Number of releases')
plt.show()

In addition to the fracture in 2008, the chart also shows other small periods of market downturns in 1998, 2002, 2015. All these breaking points are associated with the general economic situation. In all of these years, there were recessions in the world economy.
The gaming industry is highly dependent on investor money. During economic downturns, the flow of investment in the industry declines.
As you know, in 2008 there was an economic crisis that hit many industries hard. As we can see from the graph, the games industry was unable to recover its previous growth and since then the market volume has been steadily declining.
By 2016, only 9 gaming platforms remained alive, of which only 3 have a significant annual turnover.

The study of the reasons for such a fall in the market is not the subject of this study, however, it can be assumed that the downward trend in all gaming platforms is due to the emergence of new platforms for games such as smartphones and platforms for browser online games. And also as a result of the fact that selling games are no longer the main business goal for game developers. Games have become a platform for permanent earnings for game manufacturers from in-game currency, for the sale of various game items and additional gaming options. Many games have therefore become free.

Another problem for professional game sellers was the impossibility of entering the market for mobile applications. Google and Apple have essentially become monopolists in selling games on their platforms. It's a sad fact that market competition kills, but game sellers have to play by these rules.

Recommendations and forecasts for 2017 and the coming years:

  • I recommend to continue selling games on the following platforms: PS4, Xbox One, Nintendo 3DS, PC.
  • I propose to focus not only on the selling games but also on other goods from the world of games, such as gaming currency cards, game consoles, and other gaming equipment, souvenirs, clothing, and items with a gaming identity.
  • The development of social media accounts on the basis of the existing brand, and attract a large number of subscribers can become new profit centers for an online game store.
